UPI/Online Payment Fraud


UPI (Unified Payments Interface) fraud is a common cybercrime in which attackers trick individuals into transferring money through digital payment apps. 
This type of fraud has increased significantly with the rise of online transactions.
A typical UPI fraud occurs in several steps. First, the attacker contacts the victim via phone, SMS, or social media, often pretending to be a bank official, customer support agent, or buyer.
Next, they create urgency or trust by offering rewards, refunds, or resolving fake issues.
The victim is then asked to click on a malicious link or approve a “collect request” in their UPI app. In some cases, the attacker convinces the victim to share sensitive information such as OTPs or UPI PINs.
Once the victim authorizes the transaction, money is instantly transferred to the attacker’s account.
The primary targets are students, elderly individuals, and people unfamiliar with digital payment systems.
Small business owners are also frequent victims due to regular online transactions.
The consequences can be severe, including financial loss, stress, and loss of trust in digital platforms.
In many cases, recovering the stolen money is difficult.
This crime can be prevented by never sharing UPI PINs or OTPs, carefully verifying payment requests, and avoiding unknown links or calls. 
Awareness and caution are key to staying safe.
